00:00:00.690 --> 00:00:03.970
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington, DC.

00:00:21.370 --> 00:00:24.270
&gt;&gt; Mary-Jane Deeb: Welcome,
welcome to the Library of Congress.

00:00:24.270 --> 00:00:28.040
I'm really very happy to see
you all here for what promises

00:00:28.040 --> 00:00:32.150
to be a very exciting program.

00:00:32.150 --> 00:00:34.190
I'm Mary-Jane Deeb,
chief of the African

00:00:34.190 --> 00:00:37.120
and Middle Eastern Division
here at the Library.

00:00:37.120 --> 00:00:41.180
And I make a little
ad for our division.

00:00:41.180 --> 00:00:44.500
Our division is made up of
three sections, the African,

00:00:44.500 --> 00:00:47.910
the Near Eastern, and
the Hebraic Sections.

00:00:47.910 --> 00:00:52.870
We're responsible for materials
from 78 countries in the Near East,

00:00:52.870 --> 00:00:55.340
Central Asia, the Caucusus as well

00:00:55.340 --> 00:00:58.160
as from the entire
continent of Africa.

00:00:58.160 --> 00:01:01.340
We also serve these
materials to patrons here

00:01:01.340 --> 00:01:04.900
in our reading room
and around the Library.

00:01:04.900 --> 00:01:10.190
And we organize programs, exhibits,
conferences and other activities

00:01:10.190 --> 00:01:11.830
that highlight these collections.

00:01:11.830 --> 00:01:14.800
And that inform our
patrons about the countries

00:01:14.800 --> 00:01:18.710
and cultures these
publications come from.

00:01:18.710 --> 00:01:23.010
The African Section has been
partnering for the past five years

00:01:23.010 --> 00:01:27.590
on a special series entitled
"Conversations with African Poets

00:01:27.590 --> 00:01:30.670
and Writers" and has been
partnering with the Poetry

00:01:30.670 --> 00:01:34.360
and Literature Center at the
Library and the Africa Society

00:01:34.360 --> 00:01:36.780
of the National Summit on Africa.

00:01:36.780 --> 00:01:40.890
So we were delighted to meet
with Kwame Dawes, founding member

00:01:40.890 --> 00:01:45.380
of the African Poetry Book Fund
and editor of the Prairie Schooner,

00:01:45.380 --> 00:01:50.080
a couple of months ago over
dinner and we began discussing

00:01:50.080 --> 00:01:54.800
and planning this very special
event today on African poetry

00:01:54.800 --> 00:01:58.220
which fitted right in with
what we had been doing

00:01:58.220 --> 00:02:00.820
for the past five years.

00:02:00.820 --> 00:02:06.780
So I very much hope that this
program is only the first,

00:02:06.780 --> 00:02:09.560
on the beginning of
many programs to come

00:02:09.560 --> 00:02:12.290
that we will all be doing together.

00:02:12.290 --> 00:02:16.510
So now, I would like to
recognize Professor Kwame Dawes

00:02:16.510 --> 00:02:19.950
and to thank him for bringing
the African Poetry Book Fund

00:02:19.950 --> 00:02:21.430
to the Library.

00:02:21.430 --> 00:02:24.860
I would also like to thank
all those who have made this

00:02:24.860 --> 00:02:27.990
and all the other programs
in the series possible.

00:02:27.990 --> 00:02:32.910
Of course, Rob Casper, the dynamo,
the head of the Poetry Center

00:02:32.910 --> 00:02:39.080
and Anya Creightney, the partner
in this endeavor who has worked

00:02:39.080 --> 00:02:43.180
so very hard on the Library side
to put the program together.

00:02:43.180 --> 00:02:47.250 position:56%
As well as our long-term partners in
the Conversations with African Poets

00:02:47.250 --> 00:02:51.820
and Writers, the President of the
Africa Society, Patricia Baine,

00:02:51.820 --> 00:02:54.090
and the Chairperson
