00:14:51.050 --> 00:14:52.350
&gt;&gt; Good afternoon.

00:14:52.350 --> 00:14:53.650
&gt;&gt; Mary-Jane Deeb: And
then we're all here

00:14:53.650 --> 00:14:57.640
and we need to put this thing on.

00:15:03.220 --> 00:15:08.380
Okay. So I was going to say -- my
first question was going to say,

00:15:08.380 --> 00:15:11.310
it was going to be --
why are you involved

00:15:11.310 --> 00:15:13.490
with the African Poetry Book Fund?

00:15:13.490 --> 00:15:17.310
But now you know [laughter]
after having heard Kwame speak,

00:15:17.310 --> 00:15:19.610
you know, why they're involved.

00:15:19.610 --> 00:15:21.590
But I'm still going
to ask the question.

00:15:21.590 --> 00:15:25.780
I want each of you -- I'm going to
ask each of you to say something

00:15:25.780 --> 00:15:32.380
about themselves but also
in addition to Kwame Dawes,

00:15:32.380 --> 00:15:35.910
why did you, why are you
part of this project?

00:15:35.910 --> 00:15:42.580
Why, what you think your role
is, should be and, you know,

00:15:42.580 --> 00:15:45.310
how you feel you're
contributing to this project?

00:15:45.310 --> 00:15:47.750
&gt;&gt; Chris Abani: Okay,
hi, you can hear me?

00:15:47.750 --> 00:15:50.150
All right, I always have
to check like a big man

00:15:50.150 --> 00:15:52.450
with a small voice [laughter].

00:15:53.610 --> 00:15:58.500
And so, I think for me, perhaps
historically among the group,

00:15:58.500 --> 00:16:02.580
apart from probably Bernardine,
have known Kwame the longest.

00:16:02.580 --> 00:16:05.860
And it's on to more
than 20 years now.

00:16:05.860 --> 00:16:07.160
&gt;&gt; Kwame Dawes: Yeah.

00:16:07.160 --> 00:16:08.460
&gt;&gt; Chris Abani: And
what people don't know

00:16:08.460 --> 00:16:12.580
but my first ever poetry workshop
was with Kwame Dawes in London

00:16:12.580 --> 00:16:15.300
and so Kwame started something
called the Afro Star School

00:16:15.300 --> 00:16:17.180
of Poetry and he would
come to London,

00:16:17.180 --> 00:16:19.160
black British poets had no mentors.

00:16:19.160 --> 00:16:20.730
And he would run this workshop.

00:16:20.730 --> 00:16:23.680
And we all were kind of very cocky

00:16:23.680 --> 00:16:26.060
and assumed we knew what we
were talking about and then

00:16:26.060 --> 00:16:30.130
like I think the first hour, Kwame
sent everyone into like panic.

00:16:30.130 --> 00:16:33.760
He's, you know, people were
like, yeah, I'm a poet, you know.

00:16:33.760 --> 00:16:35.570 position:56%
Like I've been writing for 15 years.

00:16:35.570 --> 00:16:37.410
And Kwame was, "Oh,
that's interesting.

00:16:37.410 --> 00:16:39.830
What is your typical
syllabic count per line?"

00:16:39.830 --> 00:16:43.380
And they're like what.

00:16:43.380 --> 00:16:46.570
So Kwame, I sort of have
known and sort of --

00:16:46.570 --> 00:16:51.870
I have seen Kwame do things that
Calabash started as a conversation

00:16:51.870 --> 00:16:56.000
with Colin Channer in this
aisle of a supermarket.

00:16:56.000 --> 00:16:58.160
We were buying orange juice

00:16:58.160 --> 00:17:01.260
and we couldn't find the
large orange juice in England.

00:17:01.260 --> 00:17:04.370
And Colin said, I'm so tired of
the way the English would put on --

00:17:04.370 --> 00:17:05.670
no big orange juice, you know.

00:17:05.670 --> 00:17:09.450
[Laughter] It's just like them for
small, small festival and things.

00:17:09.450 --> 00:17:12.890
And Kwame said, "Want me to
do a big festival, you know."

00:17:12.890 --> 00:17:15.370
And so I was coming up
behind and I said, "Oh,

00:17:15.370 --> 00:17:18.600
we're going to need
a calabash for this."

00:17:18.600 --> 00:17:19.900
&gt;&gt; Mary-Jane Deeb: Absolutely.

00:17:19.900 --> 00:17:21.200
&gt;&gt; Chris Abani: And
so, what is it is

00:17:21.200 --> 00:17:23.930
where other people have planning
meetings to have planning meetings,

00:17:23.930 --> 00:17:28.380
an idea occurs and from
the moment of the inception

00:17:28.380 --> 00:17:31.670
of the idea is already the
planning and implementation of it.

00:17:31.670 --> 00:17:36.180
So this idea that Kwame has
always had which is to give,

00:17:36.180 --> 00:17:41.220
that we as a particular generation
of writers, did not always benefit

00:17:41.220 --> 00:17:42.690
from a generation that
came before us.

00:17:42.690 --> 00:17:45.680
And so his commitment from
the beginning has always been

00:17:45.680 --> 00:17:50.620
to provide access and to try to
create an institution around access

00:17:50.620 --> 00:17:54.940
that will sustain itself beyond
an individual generosity.

00:17:54.940 --> 00:17:56.330
And that's why I bought into it.

00:17:56.330 --> 00:17:57.630
It's very simple.

00:17:57.630 --> 00:17:58.930
&gt;&gt; Mary-Jane Deeb: Wonderful.

00:17:58.930 --> 00:18:01.400
What about you, Matthew?

00:18:01.400 --> 00:18:02.700
&gt;&gt; Matthew Shenoda: Hello.

00:18:02.700 --> 00:18:05.000
Sometimes, I do smile [laughter].

00:18:06.820 --> 00:18:12.380
You know, I think quite
similarly to Chris.

00:18:12.380 --> 00:18:14.210
For me, I think it has been --

00:18:14.210 --> 00:18:16.610
I've always been someone
who's believed very deeply

00:18:16.610 --> 00:18:18.310
in institution building

00:18:18.310 --> 00:18:21.420
and in creating something
outside of one's self.

00:18:21.420 --> 00:18:26.710
And I think having met Kwame some
years ago and seen what he does

00:18:26.710 --> 00:18:29.320
when he first approached
me with this idea,

00:18:29.320 --> 00:18:31.820
I knew that this would
actually happen, right.

00:18:31.820 --> 00:18:34.020
So that was the other
thing, that the investment

00:18:34.020 --> 00:18:36.940
of this energy was
going to go somewhere.

00:18:36.940 --> 00:18:39.810
And that we would be
able to create something

00:18:39.810 --> 00:18:41.720
that we hope will live beyond us

00:18:41.720 --> 00:18:44.600
which I think is something
I was always raised with.

00:18:44.600 --> 00:18:45.980
I was always raised with this idea

00:18:45.980 --> 00:18:49.250
that you can't just
do what you do, right.

00:18:49.250 --> 00:18:51.400
That that you have to
take an active role

00:18:51.400 --> 00:18:54.120
in building community in some way.

00:18:54.120 --> 00:18:58.780
And I think for many of us, as
writers in this country who come,

00:18:58.780 --> 00:19:01.260
you know, from various
places and lived in this kind

00:19:01.260 --> 00:19:04.100
of diasporic space,
we've not had that.

00:19:04.100 --> 00:19:05.480
We have not had the space.

00:19:05.480 --> 00:19:10.370
And so I love the kind of audacity
of the idea of making a space

00:19:10.370 --> 00:19:13.990
where we could fit into a space
that would actually hold us,

00:19:13.990 --> 00:19:17.450
a space that would be a
foundation for the future

00:19:17.450 --> 00:19:19.110
of who we are and what we do.

00:19:19.110 --> 00:19:21.890
And then of course, just
the incredible need.

00:19:21.890 --> 00:19:28.300
There is, to me, an incredibly like
simple practicality to all of this,

00:19:28.300 --> 00:19:30.660
right, that there is no space

00:19:30.660 --> 00:19:33.780
that is publishing
contemporary African poetry

00:19:33.780 --> 00:19:37.010
in the English language
in any sustainable way.

00:19:37.010 --> 00:19:41.630
So the idea is just brilliant in
its simplicity and I think all

00:19:41.630 --> 00:19:44.750
of that alone and then working with
these folks -- as Kwame said --

00:19:44.750 --> 00:19:47.590
I have never -- I've
worked in a lot of places.

00:19:47.590 --> 00:19:52.000
I've never worked with a group of
people this easy, this committed

00:19:52.000 --> 00:19:56.760
and who just don't -- you know,
nobody asked questions in the sense

00:19:56.760 --> 00:19:58.650
of why are we doing this?

00:19:58.650 --> 00:20:03.250
Everyone is just there and doing
the work and laughing through it

00:20:03.250 --> 00:20:05.890
which I think is important as well.

00:20:05.890 --> 00:20:08.810
&gt;&gt; Aracelis Girmay: Thank you.

00:20:08.810 --> 00:20:10.110
Can you hear me?

00:20:10.110 --> 00:20:11.410
&gt;&gt; Yeah.

00:20:11.410 --> 00:20:14.290
&gt;&gt; Aracelis Girmay: I --
I mean, as Kwame said,

00:20:14.290 --> 00:20:20.150 position:56%
I've just joined the editorial board
and was thrilled to have been asked

00:20:20.150 --> 00:20:24.220
and I've gone to the first cycle.

00:20:24.220 --> 00:20:30.080
But before I joined the board,
I remember getting my first box,

00:20:30.080 --> 00:20:34.200
the little Chapbook box and just
had been so excited and [inaudible]

00:20:34.200 --> 00:20:39.340
and all that and thinking, which am
I going to read first [laughter]?

00:20:39.340 --> 00:20:43.120
And lamenting but it was
a short-lived lament.

00:20:43.120 --> 00:20:47.680
Lamenting the fact that I
hadn't grown with these voices

00:20:47.680 --> 00:20:53.780
and then realizing as somebody
who believes that time is strange

00:20:53.780 --> 00:20:56.720
and complicated that
these were voices --

00:20:56.720 --> 00:20:58.940
these are voices that
are raised in me.

00:20:58.940 --> 00:21:03.140
And stretching my vision
and my languages

00:21:03.140 --> 00:21:08.840 position:56%
and so I just feel immense gratitude
to everyone who has anything to do

00:21:08.840 --> 00:21:16.900
with the poetry book fund and out
of love and greed maybe to listen

00:21:16.900 --> 00:21:22.930
as much as I can and to be a
part, you know, no question.

00:21:22.930 --> 00:21:25.000
That's why.

00:21:25.000 --> 00:21:26.300 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Mary-Jane Deeb: That's wonderful.

00:21:26.300 --> 00:21:28.600
So --

00:21:34.230 --> 00:21:36.070
And so I'm going -- I'm
going to read out the mission

00:21:36.070 --> 00:21:40.390
of the African Poetry Book Fund.

00:21:40.390 --> 00:21:44.350
It has a very broad mission.

00:21:44.350 --> 00:21:50.190
"It promotes and advances the
development and publication

00:21:50.190 --> 00:21:55.590 position:56%
of the poetic arts of Africa through
its book series, contests, workshops

00:21:55.590 --> 00:22:01.350
and seminars and through its
collaborations with publishers,

00:22:01.350 --> 00:22:06.480
[inaudible], booking agents,
colleges, universities, conferences

00:22:06.480 --> 00:22:09.190
and all other entities
