00:22:09.190 --> 00:22:11.650
in the poetic arts of Africa."

00:22:13.040 --> 00:22:18.110
Being the head of a small
division of poetic people,

00:22:18.110 --> 00:22:23.330
I think that this is an
enormous -- an enormous task.

00:22:23.330 --> 00:22:28.940
So looking at the three of
you, I just wanted to ask,

00:22:28.940 --> 00:22:33.310
do you see yourself
as performing a part,

00:22:33.310 --> 00:22:37.120
a specific part of
that overall vision?

00:22:37.120 --> 00:22:41.070
Does each one of you
have a different part

00:22:41.070 --> 00:22:43.390 position:56%
or a different role in that mission?

00:22:43.390 --> 00:22:47.470
Usually when one sits on the
board, you know, you say, okay,

00:22:47.470 --> 00:22:49.210
these are the strengths
of the people

00:22:49.210 --> 00:22:50.650
or this person or that person.

00:22:50.650 --> 00:22:52.320
They complement each other.

00:22:52.320 --> 00:22:55.140
And each one, in a way,
does something else.

00:22:55.140 --> 00:23:01.430
I might be -- I might be asking a
very non-poetic question, a very --

00:23:01.430 --> 00:23:07.470
but I was wonder, as you are
leading this organization

00:23:07.470 --> 00:23:12.030
and this initiative which is it's
very, very exciting, very new.

00:23:12.030 --> 00:23:15.290
Do you see yourselves as
performing a specific role?

00:23:15.290 --> 00:23:22.800 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Chris Abani: I actually like to
-- I don't know how many of you know

00:23:22.800 --> 00:23:25.990
about Rastafarians but
I think in a way --

00:23:25.990 --> 00:23:29.080
we have a friend that talks
about being a secular Raster

00:23:29.080 --> 00:23:34.310 position:56%
and the idea is that Rasters don't
-- there's an implicit understanding

00:23:34.310 --> 00:23:38.650
about a network and
about a hierarchy.

00:23:38.650 --> 00:23:41.550
But it is not a western
notion of hierarchy.

00:23:41.550 --> 00:23:45.680 position:56%
So like we have to meet or at least,
I have been around for a length

00:23:45.680 --> 00:23:47.910
of time where Kwame
has two nicknames.

00:23:47.910 --> 00:23:51.080
One is Father Dawes
because he's the father.

00:23:51.080 --> 00:23:54.510
And the second is Noah
because he knows everything.

00:23:54.510 --> 00:24:00.040
[ Laughter ]

00:24:00.040 --> 00:24:01.550
So I think it really
works like this.

00:24:01.550 --> 00:24:03.120
The father puts out a call.

00:24:03.120 --> 00:24:04.420
&gt;&gt; Mary-Jane Deeb: Okay.

00:24:04.420 --> 00:24:05.720
&gt;&gt; Chris Abani: And
the disciples answer.

00:24:05.720 --> 00:24:09.340 position:56%
So sometimes, when Kwame -- I don't
sleep but Kwame doesn't sleep at all

00:24:09.340 --> 00:24:13.420
and so I'll wake up at -- I
don't know, like 8:00 A.M.

00:24:13.420 --> 00:24:17.860
and they'll have -- you see the
first email from Kwame and it goes

00:24:17.860 --> 00:24:21.360
out and says, "[Inaudible],
we need to do this.

00:24:21.360 --> 00:24:23.510
Who can help?"

00:24:23.510 --> 00:24:25.390
He has twins so he's
always up next [laughter].

00:24:25.390 --> 00:24:30.750
And then you'll see a response
where maybe Kwame says,

00:24:30.750 --> 00:24:32.050
"We need to do something at AWP.

00:24:32.050 --> 00:24:34.000
I need a proposal written."

00:24:34.000 --> 00:24:37.210
I wake up and within 10
minutes of that email going out,

00:24:37.210 --> 00:24:43.380 position:56%
he has detailed a proposal which
then goes to Kwame who then sends it

00:24:43.380 --> 00:24:46.960 position:56%
to me and then within two-and-a-half
hours, it's already at AWP.

00:24:46.960 --> 00:24:50.280
So it's the same -- Kwame
may say, "We have a Library

00:24:50.280 --> 00:24:53.660
of Congress event," and so
it's sort of like everyone,

00:24:53.660 --> 00:24:54.960
there are things we are all --

00:24:54.960 --> 00:24:57.870
we do better than others
but I think it's just --

00:24:57.870 --> 00:25:00.020
it's never really thought
of in that way.

00:25:00.020 --> 00:25:04.460
Instead of this is a house we're
all building, whenever you wake up,

00:25:04.460 --> 00:25:06.910
you pick up the shovel
and you start doing it.

00:25:06.910 --> 00:25:08.580
So there's that part of it.

00:25:08.580 --> 00:25:11.730
But I think that it's really
this idea that what we're trying

00:25:11.730 --> 00:25:14.360
to create is a living archive.

00:25:14.360 --> 00:25:17.040
We don't think of the archive
as something that is just there.

00:25:17.040 --> 00:25:19.790
It's alive all the time and it kind
of goes into what you are talking

00:25:19.790 --> 00:25:24.570
about this notion of a
strange idea of time.

00:25:24.570 --> 00:25:28.270
You have to imagine the
thousands of entries we get

00:25:28.270 --> 00:25:32.280
and then you get assigned
60 to a hundred and it's

00:25:32.280 --> 00:25:33.620 position:56%
like we need a turnaround in a week.

00:25:33.620 --> 00:25:36.800
It's something that's so -- you
start reading it and then you come

00:25:36.800 --> 00:25:40.180
across voices like these
voices sitting here.

00:25:40.180 --> 00:25:44.720 position:56%
And you -- something happens --
there's a real humbling that happens

00:25:44.720 --> 00:25:47.710
to us reading it because
you start to --

00:25:47.710 --> 00:25:49.960
you know, there are moments
when Kwame would just call me

00:25:49.960 --> 00:25:51.650
and be like, hey, listen
to this line.

00:25:51.650 --> 00:25:53.860
And he would read me
a line from Safia.

00:25:53.860 --> 00:25:55.790
And I said, "Who the
hell wrote that?"

00:25:55.790 --> 00:25:57.590
And he's like, your cousin.

00:25:57.590 --> 00:26:02.040
[ Laughter ]

00:26:02.040 --> 00:26:06.900
So I think that what the scope of
it, there is a whole and you know

00:26:06.900 --> 00:26:09.510
like Matthew told [inaudible],
the Pan African notion of this

00:26:09.510 --> 00:26:12.810
because oftentimes you find
that literature tends to kind

00:26:12.810 --> 00:26:15.230
of have been very focalized
around West Africa

00:26:15.230 --> 00:26:16.880
and Southern Africa
coming from the continent.

00:26:16.880 --> 00:26:18.350
But we don't subscribe to that.

00:26:18.350 --> 00:26:20.810
But I think what sustains
in this context

00:26:20.810 --> 00:26:24.050
of creating this is
that we are transformed.

00:26:24.050 --> 00:26:26.840
It is not -- I don't feel like
we are giving things to people.

00:26:26.840 --> 00:26:29.340
I think that they are
giving things to us.

00:26:29.340 --> 00:26:30.640
They make our works --

00:26:30.640 --> 00:26:31.940
&gt;&gt; Mary-Jane Deeb: So
it comes both ways.

00:26:31.940 --> 00:26:33.460
&gt;&gt; Chris Abani: It comes
more towards us, I think,

00:26:33.460 --> 00:26:35.490
than people can often
really imagine.

00:26:35.490 --> 00:26:37.170
It transforms your work.

00:26:37.170 --> 00:26:39.180
It transforms your notion of self

00:26:39.180 --> 00:26:43.460
because you're encountering African
voices you didn't even know existed

00:26:43.460 --> 00:26:47.720 position:56%
that articulates in an experience
for you that you know at a DNA level

00:26:47.720 --> 00:26:50.360
but have never thought to
articulate in this way.

00:26:50.360 --> 00:26:52.460
So all of it is really about --

00:26:52.460 --> 00:26:55.550
it's more for me, the
gift that it expands us.

00:26:55.550 --> 00:26:58.530
And that, in turn, expansion
I think sustains this idea

00:26:58.530 --> 00:27:02.170
of the global expansion
and so it makes it so easy

00:27:02.170 --> 00:27:04.450
to pass the mission statement.

00:27:04.450 --> 00:27:06.820
I think what that says
is not even --

00:27:06.820 --> 00:27:09.720
it doesn't even come close
to the gift it is to people

00:27:09.720 --> 00:27:11.020
who work within this field.

00:27:11.020 --> 00:27:13.870
&gt;&gt; Mary-Jane Deeb: Okay, lovely.

00:27:13.870 --> 00:27:15.920
&gt;&gt; Matthew Shenoda:
Yeah, I think for me,

00:27:15.920 --> 00:27:19.330
the thing is that the work
always comes first, right.

00:27:19.330 --> 00:27:20.830
And I mean the work of the poet.

00:27:20.830 --> 00:27:23.240
That is at the center of this.

00:27:23.240 --> 00:27:25.440
So in terms of a division of labor,

00:27:25.440 --> 00:27:27.790
I think we all just do
whatever needs to get done.

00:27:27.790 --> 00:27:30.970
We all have certain skillsets
