"Okay, gentlemen.

00:32:04.190 --> 00:32:05.490
So what's next?"

00:32:05.490 --> 00:32:09.110
And I think we talked for like
20 minutes and I was taking --

00:32:09.110 --> 00:32:10.410
one of us was taking notes.

00:32:10.410 --> 00:32:12.910
And then we all kind
of know now what's next

00:32:12.910 --> 00:32:14.810
and it will start evolving.

00:32:14.810 --> 00:32:18.030
But just so that I
know, we try not to --

00:32:18.030 --> 00:32:21.190
the fact that there is no hierarchy
and no defined plan, it's not --

00:32:21.190 --> 00:32:24.460 position:56%
we're not running it, you know, like
a Nigerian storefront, you know.

00:32:24.460 --> 00:32:26.960
Hey, you [laughter] -- where
you're running to five different

00:32:26.960 --> 00:32:29.760
who will tell you the same five
different things all the time.

00:32:29.760 --> 00:32:33.120
It's very -- it's a choreography,
but it's a choreography

00:32:33.120 --> 00:32:38.150
where we trust implicitly that sort
of like sometimes, we'll be talking

00:32:38.150 --> 00:32:40.950
and Kwame will say to
Matthew, why don't you do this?

00:32:40.950 --> 00:32:42.470
And Matthew will, I
think Chris is --

00:32:42.470 --> 00:32:44.110
why don't you handle that
and I'll handle this?

00:32:44.110 --> 00:32:45.410
And there's no [inaudible].

00:32:45.410 --> 00:32:46.710
It just gets done.

00:32:46.710 --> 00:32:49.950
So there is definitely, we
look to Kwame as the hub.

00:32:49.950 --> 00:32:51.690
And we trust implicitly.

00:32:51.690 --> 00:32:58.480 position:56%
He has an intuitive understanding of
the spirit of how things can work.

00:32:58.480 --> 00:33:00.210 position:56%
And then he knows how to execute it.

00:33:00.210 --> 00:33:01.760
So there is definitely
that part of it.

00:33:01.760 --> 00:33:03.060
I hope this answers the question.

00:33:03.060 --> 00:33:04.360
&gt;&gt; Mary-Jane Deeb: Yes.

00:33:04.360 --> 00:33:06.470
No, no, no -- it does,
it does, it does.

00:33:06.470 --> 00:33:11.450
Okay, so I am going to ask
you something else now.

00:33:12.890 --> 00:33:14.560
Why don't you say something now?

00:33:14.560 --> 00:33:18.870 position:56%
Why don't you tell us something
about the poets that we're featuring

00:33:18.870 --> 00:33:23.280
because after all, you have been
the people who have selected it

00:33:23.280 --> 00:33:31.980
and how do you as editors respond
to the Chapbook winner's work

00:33:31.980 --> 00:33:35.070
and what have you done from this?

00:33:35.070 --> 00:33:39.110
I mean, you're being involved
with this for quite a while

00:33:39.110 --> 00:33:45.310
and you've made a selection
and how does that come about?

00:33:45.310 --> 00:33:47.870
So you see I'm sort of
building from organization to --

00:33:47.870 --> 00:33:49.170
&gt;&gt; Chris Abani: Yes,
to the editorial.

00:33:49.170 --> 00:33:52.620
&gt;&gt; Mary-Jane Deeb: So you see from
the general to the more specific.

00:33:52.620 --> 00:33:56.440
&gt;&gt; Chris Abani: I should also point
out that the Chapbook box sets

00:33:56.440 --> 00:33:59.200
which are remarkable are
only part of what we do.

00:33:59.200 --> 00:34:00.510
We do first book prizes.

00:34:00.510 --> 00:34:03.590
We do -- we kind of
reintroduce poets

00:34:03.590 --> 00:34:05.770
that may have been
forgotten over time.

00:34:05.770 --> 00:34:09.940
And we bring into existence
people who were not

00:34:09.940 --> 00:34:13.020
like in Patricia's [inaudible]
who have a body of work

00:34:13.020 --> 00:34:18.230
but who we realize can -- that
what we can do is position

00:34:18.230 --> 00:34:22.090
in a particular way that
allows the full range

00:34:22.090 --> 00:34:24.230
of who they are to come about.

00:34:24.230 --> 00:34:28.320
So I mean, the very basic thing
is we get all these submissions

00:34:28.320 --> 00:34:30.780
and everyone gets assigned
a reading list.

00:34:30.780 --> 00:34:34.190
And then we narrow down to finals
and then we talk about that.

00:34:34.190 --> 00:34:36.480
And it's always kind of incredible

00:34:36.480 --> 00:34:38.230
that there's never
really a lot of debate.

00:34:38.230 --> 00:34:42.000
It almost -- it's almost
instinctively you find the books

00:34:42.000 --> 00:34:43.300
that work.

00:34:43.300 --> 00:34:44.830
And then what Kwame
and I would do --

00:34:44.830 --> 00:34:47.220
because we primarily focus on
the Chapbooks is then to go

00:34:47.220 --> 00:34:51.250
through books of work almost ready
for book but aren't quite ready.

00:34:51.250 --> 00:34:54.090
And then we begin the conversation
with the poet where we say, look,

00:34:54.090 --> 00:34:55.530
there's this option
we can offer you.

00:34:55.530 --> 00:34:56.830
Are you interested?

00:34:56.830 --> 00:35:01.980
And what we do is offer -- because
we're dealing with not just people

00:35:01.980 --> 00:35:05.080
on the continent but also
continent -- a kind of --

00:35:05.080 --> 00:35:07.990
a kind of way in which writers

00:35:07.990 --> 00:35:12.530
of color are not always offered
respectful mentoring which means

00:35:12.530 --> 00:35:15.490
that we hold you to
extremely high standards.

00:35:15.490 --> 00:35:20.220
But we hold you to those standards
with an intuitive understanding

00:35:20.220 --> 00:35:24.660 position:56%
that if you do what we're asking you
to do, you will become excellent.

00:35:24.660 --> 00:35:27.110 position:56%
And this is how we just live anyway.

00:35:27.110 --> 00:35:29.930 position:56%
So we do that and we're very strict.

00:35:29.930 --> 00:35:32.410
When we give people deadlines
and there, we have incidents

00:35:32.410 --> 00:35:33.820 position:56%
where people don't meet the deadline

00:35:33.820 --> 00:35:35.910
and then we just roll
over to the next poet.

00:35:35.910 --> 00:35:39.590
And they come back, you know,
[inaudible] next try, next year.

00:35:39.590 --> 00:35:41.630
And so it gets around
but you know, you go --

00:35:41.630 --> 00:35:43.950
we do a lot of international
festivals and you --

00:35:43.950 --> 00:35:47.160
I was recently at the
Ake Festival in Nigeria.

00:35:47.160 --> 00:35:51.000
And this young man comes up to me
and says, "How much do I owe you?"

00:35:51.000 --> 00:35:55.200
And I said, "Who are you
and what do you mean?"

00:35:55.200 --> 00:35:56.500
[Laughter] Not because, you know --

00:35:56.500 --> 00:35:57.800
because I was thinking well
how much can I get from you?

00:35:57.800 --> 00:36:00.540
No, I was kidding [laughter].

00:36:00.540 --> 00:36:01.840
So he was one of the poets.

00:36:01.840 --> 00:36:04.120
I had never met him that we
had mentored in this way.

00:36:04.120 --> 00:36:06.400
But the idea is that
he couldn't understand.

00:36:06.400 --> 00:36:10.620
He actually thought there was going
to be a bill for the amount of work

00:36:10.620 --> 00:36:13.240
that went into mentoring him
and the fact that he's going

00:36:13.240 --> 00:36:15.110
to get these books
and they're published

00:36:15.110 --> 00:36:16.590
and he gets all these copies.

00:36:16.590 --> 00:36:19.850
And the notion that
he doesn't have to --

00:36:19.850 --> 00:36:23.820
that all is required of him
is to step into his own power.

00:36:23.820 --> 00:36:26.560
Sometimes, it's something
that is foreign.

00:36:26.560 --> 00:36:30.990 position:56%
And so that is part of how -- so the
editorial process is not just a --

00:36:30.990 --> 00:36:33.760
it is also about the poems
but it also becomes ways

00:36:33.760 --> 00:36:40.260
in which inadvertently you're work
shopping people into an acceptance

00:36:40.260 --> 00:36:42.370
of how powerful they are.

00:36:42.370 --> 00:36:45.440
And so it becomes easy
for us in that way.

00:36:45.440 --> 00:36:49.960
And then we get together
and then Kwame says to me,

00:36:49.960 --> 00:36:52.420
I need your introduction.

00:36:52.420 --> 00:36:53.720
And I'm like, when do you need it?

00:36:53.720 --> 00:36:56.720
Well, yesterday would
have been nice.

00:36:56.720 --> 00:36:59.880 position:56%
[Laughter] And you know, oftentimes,
we work under such high pressure

00:36:59.880 --> 00:37:02.490
but it's very easy and
it's a back and forth.

00:37:02.490 --> 00:37:07.140
And then we have incidents where
we assign particular writers

00:37:07.140 --> 00:37:09.690
to other -- you know,
editors who and we say,

00:37:09.690 --> 00:37:11.230
work with this person specifically.

00:37:11.230 --> 00:37:13.500
We have Helen Yitah who's been work

00:37:13.500 --> 00:37:17.220
to help really bring Amah Ata
Aidoo's work back into public.

00:37:17.220 --> 00:37:22.660
And sometimes, we're
asking poets, you know --

00:37:22.660 --> 00:37:25.320
we're asking poets who -- you
know how hard it is to say

00:37:25.320 --> 00:37:28.510 position:56%
to [Inaudible], I read this poem and
I think you should change this line.

00:37:28.510 --> 00:37:32.320
[ Laughter ]

00:37:32.320 --> 00:37:35.470
So -- well, I'm asking people
whom you're kind of holding

00:37:35.470 --> 00:37:39.020
in a certain kind of reverence
at the same time to like --

00:37:39.020 --> 00:37:40.320
&gt;&gt; Mary-Jane Deeb:
To make the changes.

00:37:40.320 --> 00:37:41.620
&gt;&gt; Chris Abani: To
make these changes.

00:37:41.620 --> 00:37:45.450 position:56%
And what becomes really beautiful
about it is that they respond to you

00:37:45.450 --> 00:37:50.330
in this way where they realize
they too have been hungry

00:37:50.330 --> 00:37:52.520
for a certain conversation.

00:37:52.520 --> 00:37:54.100
And not just, you know,
then being --

00:37:54.100 --> 00:37:55.400
&gt;&gt; Mary-Jane Deeb: Not
just being up there.

00:37:55.400 --> 00:37:56.700
&gt;&gt; Chris Abani: Yeah, that they --

00:37:56.700 --> 00:37:58.000
&gt;&gt; Mary-Jane Deeb:
My folks [inaudible].

00:37:58.000 --> 00:37:59.300
&gt;&gt; Chris Abani: Yeah,
then no one talks to them.

00:37:59.300 --> 00:38:00.750
They want people who could -- so
it works on all kinds of levels

00:38:00.750 --> 00:38:04.590
in this way and I don't
know if you --

00:38:04.590 --> 00:38:06.910
&gt;&gt; Matthew Shenoda: I mean, I
don't know that I have much to add

00:38:06.910 --> 00:38:08.370
to that other than the fact

00:38:08.370 --> 00:38:12.080
that that cultivation is very
important for us, I think.

00:38:12.080 --> 00:38:15.530
And for the young writers
especially those on the continent,

00:38:15.530 --> 00:38:19.810 position:56%
we know they have limited access
both to a certain body of literature

00:38:19.810 --> 00:38:22.890
as well as to workshops
and these kind of things.

00:38:22.890 --> 00:38:26.360
So we spend a lot of time back and
forth with them doing, you know,

00:38:26.360 --> 00:38:28.660
critiques and line edits
and this kind of thing.

00:38:28.660 --> 00:38:32.700 position:56%
But even for the writers in diaspora
and here in the United States,

00:38:32.700 --> 00:38:35.760
those of us who have
published extensively

00:38:35.760 --> 00:38:41.240
in this country also know the
lack of an editorial criticality

00:38:41.240 --> 00:38:46.090
that exists in the U.S. publishing
as it relates to African writers

00:38:46.090 --> 00:38:48.690
and writers of color in general.

00:38:48.690 --> 00:38:50.750
And so I think there
-- that has opened

00:38:50.750 --> 00:38:54.690
up for me some really
beautiful conversations.

00:38:54.690 --> 00:38:57.030
Like you know, Bob
Marlowe once said,

00:38:57.030 --> 00:38:59.600
"If you know who you are then you
would know where you're coming

00:38:59.600 --> 00:39:03.470
from then you wouldn't have to ask
me who the hell do I think I am."

00:39:03.470 --> 00:39:07.830
[Laughter] I think in a way, that's
almost a model for the relationship

00:39:07.830 --> 00:39:11.390
that we have with people
because there is --

00:39:11.390 --> 00:39:16.770
there is a kind of foundational
sense of who we're working with.

00:39:16.770 --> 00:39:18.940
And who they're working
with as editors

00:39:18.940 --> 00:39:22.940
that we can immediately move
the conversation to a new level

00:39:22.940 --> 00:39:26.950
and actually engage in the
work, engage in the aesthetics,

00:39:26.950 --> 00:39:30.120
engage in the craft
and what is happening.

00:39:30.120 --> 00:39:32.620 position:56%
We don't have to ask these questions

00:39:32.620 --> 00:39:34.450
about like what does
this word mean --

00:39:34.450 --> 00:39:37.580
or what's that or where do you
find this country on a map?

00:39:37.580 --> 00:39:40.590
Or I mean, this is stuff
where frankly I'm --

00:39:40.590 --> 00:39:43.310
you know, look, I mean when I
published my first book which was

00:39:43.310 --> 00:39:45.690
through a great publisher
here in the United States,

00:39:45.690 --> 00:39:51.270
I remember clearly my, you
know, white editor said,

00:39:51.270 --> 00:39:53.300
"This is really interesting
but I don't --

00:39:53.300 --> 00:39:56.110
I don't think that I can
say anything to you."

00:39:56.110 --> 00:39:57.610 position:56%
And I said, "Well, you're an editor.

00:39:57.610 --> 00:39:58.910
Isn't that your job?"

00:39:58.910 --> 00:40:01.040 position:56%
[Laughter] And he said, "Yeah, but,
you know, like it makes me nervous."

00:40:01.040 --> 00:40:03.270
And he was very honest with me.

00:40:03.270 --> 00:40:05.200
He said, "You know,
from critiquing this,

00:40:05.200 --> 00:40:07.350
I don't know about the
cultural this and that."

00:40:07.350 --> 00:40:09.010
And I just thought, all
right, we're not going

00:40:09.010 --> 00:40:11.080
to have a real conversation
here, right?

00:40:11.080 --> 00:40:15.950
Because I can't -- you know,
there's too much behind

00:40:15.950 --> 00:40:17.710
that that needs to
get a word through.

00:40:17.710 --> 00:40:20.630
And so I think that you
know, one of the great things

00:40:20.630 --> 00:40:23.450
about our team too is that we're
an incredibly diverse group

00:40:23.450 --> 00:40:24.750
of people, right.

00:40:24.750 --> 00:40:29.230 position:56%
We represent the diversity of the
African continent and its diasporas.

00:40:29.230 --> 00:40:33.670
We represent it in terms of,
you know, gender, ethnicity,

00:40:33.670 --> 00:40:37.190
language bases, aesthetic
practices, all of these things.

00:40:37.190 --> 00:40:40.670
And so I think that there's
always one of us who can connect

00:40:40.670 --> 00:40:43.930
to a writer in a very
meaningful way.

00:40:47.390 --> 00:40:50.560
&gt;&gt; Aracelis Girmay: I
don't have a [inaudible].

00:40:50.560 --> 00:40:51.860
&gt;&gt; Mary-Jane Deeb: And
those writers, do they --

00:40:51.860 --> 00:40:58.090
do they have an input
in other writers' works?

00:40:58.090 --> 00:41:00.730
In other words, let's say
you've worked with someone

00:41:00.730 --> 00:41:04.970
and you've published that person,
you go back to that person and say,

00:41:04.970 --> 00:41:07.800
well, you know, I've
read something, you know.

00:41:07.800 --> 00:41:09.320
I'd like to have your
opinion on that.

00:41:09.320 --> 00:41:11.890
Do you do that sometimes?

