00:59:42.700 --> 00:59:44.000
&gt;&gt; Mary-Jane Deeb: Chris?

00:59:44.000 --> 00:59:49.610
&gt;&gt; Chris Abani: So when
people think about terms --

00:59:49.610 --> 00:59:54.320
the terms of humanity that we bring
to other people, we -- what we --

00:59:54.320 --> 00:59:59.900
and we do this through race, class,
and gender, disability, body --

00:59:59.900 --> 01:00:06.010
we like to imagine that people have
a different inner life than we do,

01:00:06.010 --> 01:00:09.990
that a person who works at
McDonald's does not have as rich

01:00:09.990 --> 01:00:12.690
or even a richer inner
life than we do.

01:00:12.690 --> 01:00:16.260
And therefore, we think
we cannot access them.

01:00:16.260 --> 01:00:20.200
But the truth about literature
-- and this is my hope always --

01:00:20.200 --> 01:00:25.780
that I became a writer because
of James Baldwin, right,

01:00:25.780 --> 01:00:30.640
because I read "Another
Country" when I was 10 years old.

01:00:30.640 --> 01:00:34.700 position:56%
And the fact that there is no way
James Baldwin could have imagined my

01:00:34.700 --> 01:00:39.370
existence, that his book would
travel 6000 miles through time

01:00:39.370 --> 01:00:43.390
into an African country, and that
a young boy would read this book,

01:00:43.390 --> 01:00:49.590 position:56%
and who -- his entire aesthetic will
almost mirror Baldwin's in this way.

01:00:49.590 --> 01:00:52.590
So what his books are doing
is that they are proving

01:00:52.590 --> 01:00:57.230
that their inner lives, that there
is not African, there is no other.

01:00:57.230 --> 01:00:59.110
There is just human.

01:00:59.110 --> 01:01:02.000
And so my hope is that five years

01:01:02.000 --> 01:01:07.090
from now a 12-year-old white
boy will wander into a store,

01:01:07.090 --> 01:01:13.550
and in a discount bin if necessary,
find "January's Children" by Safir,

01:01:13.550 --> 01:01:16.830
