01:46:41.270 --> 01:46:42.570
I was confused.

01:46:42.570 --> 01:46:44.320
I had no words.

01:46:44.320 --> 01:46:47.070
"Come, let us go home,
Little Father.

01:46:47.070 --> 01:46:50.250
When you are of age you shall
find the words," he said.

01:46:50.250 --> 01:46:51.930
"But always be careful.

01:46:51.930 --> 01:46:54.880
To hunt a word is to hunt a life."

01:47:00.650 --> 01:47:02.630
So when I wrote --
most of these poems,

01:47:02.630 --> 01:47:04.600
when I wrote them I wasn't
writing them with a [inaudible] --

01:47:04.600 --> 01:47:07.950
they're the poems I think
I wrote because I had to,

01:47:07.950 --> 01:47:09.250
because of things that
were happening.

01:47:09.250 --> 01:47:12.800
For example, my daughter's birth.

01:47:12.800 --> 01:47:15.420
You know, so in that sense,
it's not poems I was writing

01:47:15.420 --> 01:47:17.070
with the idea of a collection.

01:47:17.070 --> 01:47:18.940
Though I don't -- I'm
not going to lie and say

01:47:18.940 --> 01:47:21.490
that I was writing
for myself, you know.

01:47:21.490 --> 01:47:23.380
But yeah, so it was for --

01:47:23.380 --> 01:47:26.600
I wrote most of these poems for
things I couldn't quite grasp.

01:47:26.600 --> 01:47:30.100
And this is for my daughter,
who is here somewhere,

01:47:30.100 --> 01:47:32.130
whom we named after my
late mother, Nyambura.

01:47:32.130 --> 01:47:37.410
So this is a play around her
name, which means bringer of rain.

01:47:37.410 --> 01:47:39.330
"In Your Name."

01:47:39.330 --> 01:47:42.240
Bringer of rain, I know
someday I will learn to call you

01:47:42.240 --> 01:47:47.460
by the name your mother and I
gave you, but for now the myriad

01:47:47.460 --> 01:47:51.210
of little names will do,
[speaking in foreign language],

01:47:51.210 --> 01:47:56.260
all names that amuse us now,
so often as they will not you.

01:47:56.260 --> 01:47:57.630
[Speaking in foreign
language] Let's face it,

01:47:57.630 --> 01:48:02.060
even hate me for having
them in a poem,

01:48:02.060 --> 01:48:05.320
but [speaking in foreign language],
Little Mother, you'll not abandon.

01:48:05.320 --> 01:48:08.570
Yes, it will first tie you
down, tongue-tie your teachers

01:48:08.570 --> 01:48:12.850
and friends, but one day your
name, Nyambura, will free you,

01:48:12.850 --> 01:48:16.320
and that which was once like a
prison will be a warm embrace,

01:48:16.320 --> 01:48:19.060
and that past from which you
come from will be an anchor

01:48:19.060 --> 01:48:24.580
and not a chain, each syllable
a reminder and an echo.

01:48:24.580 --> 01:48:28.050
Let me read my last poem,
you know, because, you know,

01:48:28.050 --> 01:48:30.130
even though I wrote the poems
before the age of Trump,

01:48:30.130 --> 01:48:33.150
I just have to say something
about Trump, you know,

01:48:33.150 --> 01:48:36.310
and I have this joke that
I was thinking about like

01:48:36.310 --> 01:48:38.670
if you really want to hide the
nuclear codes from trump, you know,

01:48:38.670 --> 01:48:46.940
put them in a library,
or [laughter] so, right.

01:48:46.940 --> 01:48:48.240
&gt;&gt; Oh! Oh!

01:48:48.240 --> 01:48:53.670
&gt;&gt; Mukoma Wa Ngugi: But you know,
but the poem is really about,

01:48:53.670 --> 01:48:57.600
you know, for most of us, you know,
who have not been in the U.S.,

01:48:57.600 --> 01:48:58.900 position:56%
we're the first-generation Africans,

01:48:58.900 --> 01:49:00.640
and we have been here
for a long time.

01:49:00.640 --> 01:49:03.350
You know, around questions of
identity that I think, you know,

01:49:03.350 --> 01:49:06.430
the Trump and his anti-immigration,
then you know,

01:49:06.430 --> 01:49:09.320
brings these questions
back to the forefront.

01:49:09.320 --> 01:49:11.510
"My Two Names."

01:49:11.510 --> 01:49:15.160
I have tried, but I'm never hungry
in Nairobi and full in Boston.

01:49:15.160 --> 01:49:18.160
No matter my will, the
parallels will not collapse.

01:49:18.160 --> 01:49:20.930
It's a [inaudible] my
stomach, this one we share.

01:49:20.930 --> 01:49:24.240
Sometimes I try for daylight
here to surprise nightfall there.

01:49:24.240 --> 01:49:26.930
By riding the divide of night
and day, the sun is large

01:49:26.930 --> 01:49:30.200
in such a place that I'm always
awake here and asleep there.

01:49:30.200 --> 01:49:33.590
I am without a name,
yet I bear two names.

01:49:33.590 --> 01:49:35.180
I am without a name.

01:49:35.180 --> 01:49:36.480
I bear four names.

01:49:36.480 --> 01:49:38.010
I'm nameless.

01:49:38.010 --> 01:49:40.110
Always outside my window,
my shadow restless

01:49:40.110 --> 01:49:42.840
like a ghost calls me
to find its parallel.

01:49:42.840 --> 01:49:45.770
When I left home, I found
it dancing here with a rope

01:49:45.770 --> 01:49:47.690
and an effigy outlined in chalk,

01:49:47.690 --> 01:49:50.770
and we took turns being
shadow and being.

01:49:50.770 --> 01:49:54.100
When I close my eyes to
this sun or moon burns teal,

01:49:54.100 --> 01:49:57.850
the world around me keeps
changing form, and I make a home.

01:49:57.850 --> 01:50:00.270
But flight, too, has a
shadow, and I fall back

01:50:00.270 --> 01:50:02.330
into things I cannot name or touch.

01:50:02.330 --> 01:50:04.470
What I cannot name, I cannot touch.

01:50:04.470 --> 01:50:07.170
One day I'll have to
speak for myself.

01:50:07.170 --> 01:50:10.830
One day in my bones, marrow-deep,
and complete like a grenade,

01:50:10.830 --> 01:50:14.380
I find remnants of
ghosts that have walked

01:50:14.380 --> 01:50:17.250
and lived hard before me
[speaking in foreign language],

01:50:17.250 --> 01:50:19.060
all born in times when
the modern collapse

01:50:19.060 --> 01:50:22.500
of parallels was a
stretcher as is treason.

01:50:22.500 --> 01:50:25.820
Home is longing not to
be in two places at once.

01:50:25.820 --> 01:50:29.560
This morning, there I woke up to
sounds of mourning and tear gas,

01:50:29.560 --> 01:50:31.680
graves as shallow as
my writing paper,

01:50:31.680 --> 01:50:34.150
deep like diamonds and coal mines.

01:50:34.150 --> 01:50:37.350
This morning here, I awoke to
a cup of tea with fresh ginger

01:50:37.350 --> 01:50:40.310
and mud, someone's black blood.

01:50:40.310 --> 01:50:42.330
There this morning 30 years ago,

01:50:42.330 --> 01:50:44.370
I witnessed Kamadi's
[assumed spelling] hanging.

01:50:44.370 --> 01:50:47.940
This morning here, 30 Puerto
Rican Nationalists were hanged.

01:50:47.940 --> 01:50:50.880
One day I will have to
speak to all of ourselves.

01:50:50.880 --> 01:50:52.680
I thank you.

01:50:52.680 --> 01:51:09.930
[ Applause ]

01:51:09.930 --> 01:51:11.230
&gt;&gt; Ladan Osmun: Good afternoon.

01:51:11.230 --> 01:51:13.970
&gt;&gt; Good afternoon.

01:51:13.970 --> 01:51:16.140
&gt;&gt; Ladan Osmun: It's always an
honor to read with the Book Fund.

01:51:16.140 --> 01:51:20.590
Thank you so much for the work that
you do, the editors, writers there,

01:51:20.590 --> 01:51:23.800
the partnership with
Prairie Schooner.

01:51:24.950 --> 01:51:30.830
So I wanted to chill a little
bit, but I could not be so close

01:51:30.830 --> 01:51:35.890
to the Supreme Court and not read
this newer poem which is written

01:51:35.890 --> 01:51:42.530
for Mohammed el Gharani who was
a juvenile Guantanamo detainee

01:51:42.530 --> 01:51:43.830
from Chad.

01:51:43.830 --> 01:51:48.650
When asked what it was that he
wanted, he said, "An apology."

01:51:48.650 --> 01:51:53.040
And because there's a sense that
he's categorized as a non-person

01:51:53.040 --> 01:51:57.120
for this form of detainment and
torture to work, it doesn't appear

01:51:57.120 --> 01:51:59.690
that that apology is forthcoming.

01:51:59.690 --> 01:52:07.730
Okay. And I want to start
with an introduction,

01:52:07.730 --> 01:52:11.540
an excerpt from Laura
Marling's "What He Wrote."

01:52:16.040 --> 01:52:18.760
Forgive me here.

01:52:18.760 --> 01:52:21.930
I cannot stay.

01:52:21.930 --> 01:52:24.790
He cut out my tongue.

01:52:24.790 --> 01:52:30.600
There is nothing to say.

01:52:30.600 --> 01:52:33.780 position:56%
Love me? Oh, Lord, he threw me away.

01:52:33.780 --> 01:52:36.790
He laughed at my sins.

01:52:36.790 --> 01:52:38.640
In his arms I must stay.

01:52:38.640 --> 01:52:43.970
He wrote, "I'm broke.

01:52:43.970 --> 01:52:46.890
Please send for me."

01:52:46.890 --> 01:52:52.040 position:56%
But I'm broken, too, and spoken for.

01:52:52.040 --> 01:52:55.320
Do not tempt me.

01:52:55.320 --> 01:53:00.800
Her skin is white, and
I'm light as the sun.

01:53:00.800 --> 01:53:05.660
So holy light shines on
the things you have done.

01:53:05.660 --> 01:53:09.400
The title of this poem comes

01:53:09.400 --> 01:53:14.990
from something a female
interrogator said to Mohammed.

01:53:14.990 --> 01:53:17.120
"Think of Me As Your Mother."

01:53:17.120 --> 01:53:24.100
It's the Ides of March, and
I have too much longing.

01:53:24.100 --> 01:53:27.840
Lions and gales replace speech.

01:53:27.840 --> 01:53:32.380 position:56%
My mind breaks in a stone courtyard.

01:53:32.380 --> 01:53:36.330 position:56%
It echoes as if played from turrets.

01:53:36.330 --> 01:53:38.740
They admit me.

01:53:38.740 --> 01:53:43.050
They put my clothes in a bin and
search my skin for marks, cuts,

01:53:43.050 --> 01:53:49.660
and bruises, verify my eyes, hair,
toes, and knuckles are black.

01:53:49.660 --> 01:53:51.690
They remove the string
from my hoodie

01:53:51.690 --> 01:53:55.330
so I won't make a noose of it.

01:53:55.330 --> 01:53:59.070
I'm too tired to laugh about that.

01:53:59.070 --> 01:54:00.720
They offer me rice.

01:54:00.720 --> 01:54:05.020
They say, "The rice is
good," and watch my face.

01:54:05.020 --> 01:54:08.130
They think they know Africans.

01:54:08.130 --> 01:54:09.850
I say nothing.

01:54:09.850 --> 01:54:12.540
They give me medicine, two kinds.

01:54:12.540 --> 01:54:15.490
I get free and yell, "I'm black!

01:54:15.490 --> 01:54:16.790
I'm black!

01:54:16.790 --> 01:54:18.090
I'm black!

01:54:18.090 --> 01:54:19.620
I'm black!

01:54:19.620 --> 01:54:20.920
I'm black!

01:54:20.920 --> 01:54:22.220
I'm black!

01:54:22.220 --> 01:54:23.520
I'm black!

01:54:23.520 --> 01:54:24.820
I'm black!

01:54:24.820 --> 01:54:26.120
I'm black!

01:54:26.120 --> 01:54:27.420
I'm black!

01:54:27.420 --> 01:54:28.720
And I've never been to a wedding."

01:54:28.720 --> 01:54:31.260 position:56%
After the medicine, I keep seeing
my black and yelling, "What is that?

01:54:31.260 --> 01:54:32.560
What is that?

01:54:32.560 --> 01:54:33.860
What is that?

01:54:33.860 --> 01:54:35.550
What is that?"

01:54:35.550 --> 01:54:37.450
They don't answer.

01:54:37.450 --> 01:54:42.520
A woman tells me to move it.

01:54:42.520 --> 01:54:46.950
She's pretending a toy
keyboard is a lie detector.

01:54:46.950 --> 01:54:51.370
I bumped her hands, and now
she has to start all over.

01:54:51.370 --> 01:54:56.290
After the medicine, I can see my
black, and it can't stop talking.

01:54:56.290 --> 01:54:58.900
It says, "I'm not a demon.

01:54:58.900 --> 01:55:00.730
I'm a ghost.

01:55:00.730 --> 01:55:04.330
They're doing the wrong
rituals on me."

01:55:04.330 --> 01:55:07.670
They took inventory of
my Keds, my Dickies,

01:55:07.670 --> 01:55:10.500
but I'm still found
without shoes or sheets.

01:55:10.500 --> 01:55:12.680
My chin stays bruised, and a sore

01:55:12.680 --> 01:55:17.350
in my mouth makes me remember my
wisdom tooth surgery when I was 17,

01:55:17.350 --> 01:55:19.750
and I had my first Muslim doctor,

01:55:19.750 --> 01:55:22.410
and he made a mistake
and gashed my cheek.

01:55:22.410 --> 01:55:24.660
And to keep from crying, he bid me

01:55:24.660 --> 01:55:27.850
to stop crying, even
though I wasn't.

01:55:27.850 --> 01:55:30.070
They'd given me cackling gas.

01:55:30.070 --> 01:55:32.880
He cooed, "Everything will be okay.

01:55:32.880 --> 01:55:34.920
Everything will be all right.

01:55:34.920 --> 01:55:36.920
Everything will be okay.

01:55:36.920 --> 01:55:39.640
Everything will be all right."

01:55:39.640 --> 01:55:45.100
I screeched, "I love myself,"
in my best Kendrick voice,

01:55:45.100 --> 01:55:47.340
spin like my feet are arabesque.

01:55:47.340 --> 01:55:48.640
They shoot me.

01:55:48.640 --> 01:55:53.400
After that medicine, I stop rapping
on tabletops and go to my bed.

01:55:53.400 --> 01:55:55.610
The mattress receives me.

01:55:55.610 --> 01:55:59.140 position:56%
I think of dark hair on a soft bely.

01:55:59.140 --> 01:56:01.640
The blanket hugs me.

01:56:01.640 --> 01:56:05.600
I think of my baby sister
sleeping on my mother's back.

01:56:05.600 --> 01:56:09.540
I stay in my bed all day
and miss all my prayers

01:56:09.540 --> 01:56:11.820
because the bed says yes and yes.

01:56:11.820 --> 01:56:13.520
I want it to say no.

01:56:13.520 --> 01:56:16.980
So it's yes and yes is real.

01:56:16.980 --> 01:56:20.800
Can you rape a bed
sleeping stubborn in it,

01:56:20.800 --> 01:56:24.840
even if its springs
tell you to get out?

01:56:24.840 --> 01:56:27.700
Tell my mother to bring
me some grease and my pick

01:56:27.700 --> 01:56:30.230
and to hide my hot hair
curler in her skirt.

01:56:30.230 --> 01:56:32.880
I already know my hair
better be laid when I lie

01:56:32.880 --> 01:56:37.660
in this therapist's face and
tell her, "I just got confused."

01:56:37.660 --> 01:56:41.090
They release me with
three brown paper bags.

01:56:41.090 --> 01:56:43.460
All their handles break.

01:56:43.460 --> 01:56:47.780
They want me to look crazy in
these streets, but I just hum Badu

01:56:47.780 --> 01:56:52.410
in the parking lot, and on the bus
break the high note, "Pack light."

01:56:52.410 --> 01:56:57.490
Every city built by the
water is way too turnt [sic],

01:56:57.490 --> 01:57:01.830
from Chicago to Istanbul, the
thin caterwaul of stray felines

01:57:01.830 --> 01:57:06.450
from mid-morning to dusk, the geese
that flew nowhere all winter holler

01:57:06.450 --> 01:57:10.100
in a knotted field
at a devilish hour.

01:57:10.100 --> 01:57:13.290
Then there are gunshots,
police cracking ribs.

01:57:13.290 --> 01:57:16.760
The volume is up too high,
too high in black ears.

01:57:16.760 --> 01:57:20.660
What do you do when a whole
city is dog whistling?

01:57:20.660 --> 01:57:25.110
A woman curses her young son.

01:57:25.110 --> 01:57:27.040
His blink is blank.

01:57:27.040 --> 01:57:29.590
They face each other hard-eyed.

01:57:29.590 --> 01:57:35.230
They have trouble translating
the Quran into English.

01:57:35.230 --> 01:57:39.270
Hell is the burning fire.

01:57:39.270 --> 01:57:44.290 position:56%
Hell is pain of mother losing child.

01:57:44.290 --> 01:57:49.530
In many places on Earth, both
definitions hold at the same time.

01:57:49.530 --> 01:57:54.810
I took my medicine, both kinds,
and don't yell out the window,

01:57:54.810 --> 01:57:58.770
"Rise like dust in
a Maya Angelou poem

01:57:58.770 --> 01:58:00.590 position:56%
and the voice of a kid reciting it."

01:58:00.590 --> 01:58:03.250
Rise like [inaudible]
concerts when they were tossed

01:58:03.250 --> 01:58:06.450
out the compound windows or
like [inaudible], or Mandela,

01:58:06.450 --> 01:58:08.610 position:56%
or anyone whose knees, or shoulders,

01:58:08.610 --> 01:58:12.350
or skulls were clubbed
in a dank prison.

01:58:12.350 --> 01:58:17.090
I wish I could take
you into my belly.

01:58:17.090 --> 01:58:21.180
I think it's the only
safe space for you.

01:58:21.180 --> 01:58:22.760
Come into my womb.

01:58:22.760 --> 01:58:25.660
You might find cinderblocks
and mixed metal.

01:58:25.660 --> 01:58:30.380
You might find teeth, and discrete
ejaculations, and rancid tears,

01:58:30.380 --> 01:58:34.520
and salvaged bits of scripture.

01:58:34.520 --> 01:58:38.960
Come into my placenta, my
electric water via dream submarine.

01:58:38.960 --> 01:58:41.300 position:56%
I will throw the key into the ocean.

01:58:41.300 --> 01:58:44.590
I am infinitely generative.

01:58:44.590 --> 01:58:47.900
You'll find your grandson
guarding you.

01:58:47.900 --> 01:58:51.710
When you're ready to leave,
he'll call to you, "All the best.

01:58:51.710 --> 01:58:54.120
Good-bye. Good-bye."

01:58:54.120 --> 01:58:55.920
Thank you.

01:58:55.920 --> 01:59:17.450
[ Applause ]

01:59:17.450 --> 01:59:18.750
&gt;&gt; Hope Wabuke: Wow.

01:59:18.750 --> 01:59:20.420
It's always the worst
to have to read

01:59:20.420 --> 01:59:23.530
after Ladan Osman,
because she's amazing.

01:59:23.530 --> 01:59:25.230
She really, really is.

01:59:25.230 --> 01:59:31.240
I want to thank you to Kwame, and
Chris, and Matthew, and Aracelis,

01:59:31.240 --> 01:59:34.510
and Patricia, and Mary-Jane,
and Rob,

01:59:34.510 --> 01:59:37.720
and everybody at the African
Poetry Book Fund, and the Library

01:59:37.720 --> 01:59:43.360
of Congress for making this
wonderful event happen.

01:59:43.360 --> 01:59:47.050
Tsitsi said it really is like
being around family, and it is,

01:59:47.050 --> 01:59:49.340
just the work that everybody does.

01:59:49.340 --> 01:59:54.020
So I wanted to read a few poems
from my tract book "Believing,"

01:59:54.020 --> 02:00:00.810 position:56%
which ABPF published, which is an
excerpt from a large poem manuscript

02:00:00.810 --> 02:00:03.120
in progress, similar [inaudible]
called the "The Body Family,"

02:00:03.120 --> 02:00:08.340
which explores my family's escape
from Amin's genocide in 1976

02:00:08.340 --> 02:00:15.170
in Uganda, where he massacred
about 300,000 people and I'm lucky

02:00:15.170 --> 02:00:18.270
that my parents were
able to come to America.

02:00:18.270 --> 02:00:23.760
So it felt timely with
what's happening right now.

02:00:23.760 --> 02:00:27.390
The first one is called
"If Not David."

02:00:27.390 --> 02:00:31.380
When the British came, they
brought their guns and their Jesus.

02:00:31.380 --> 02:00:33.770
They took our oil and diamonds.

02:00:33.770 --> 02:00:36.970
They sent our men to fight
their wars in Europe,

02:00:36.970 --> 02:00:39.310
did not send the bodies home.

02:00:39.310 --> 02:00:40.610
Amin was 18.

02:00:40.610 --> 02:00:42.940
He learned his lesson well.

02:00:42.940 --> 02:00:44.330
Kill the other.

02:00:44.330 --> 02:00:46.430
Take what is his.

02:00:46.430 --> 02:00:48.890
When Amin and his cronies
drove the British out,

02:00:48.890 --> 02:00:53.730
our country in chaos,
those already ignore.

02:00:53.730 --> 02:00:59.270
At first his killings were called
a natural byproduct of events.

02:00:59.270 --> 02:01:02.870
His buddy Obote, the new
president, promoted him.

02:01:02.870 --> 02:01:05.100
Said, "Kill more."

02:01:05.100 --> 02:01:10.590
But later, when his killings grew
too much and Obote said, "Stop,"

02:01:10.590 --> 02:01:15.730
Amin went after him too,
took the throne, and laughed.

02:01:15.730 --> 02:01:20.520
"No one can run," he said,
"faster than a bullet."

02:01:20.520 --> 02:01:23.470
At times, so many dead
bodies were thrown

02:01:23.470 --> 02:01:26.960
into the Nile River the
water stopped flowing.

02:01:26.960 --> 02:01:30.830
"Hitler," he was fond of
saying, "had the right idea."

02:01:30.830 --> 02:01:35.590
Can you hear me okay?

02:01:35.590 --> 02:01:41.510
Great. This next poem is called,
"Goliath," also about Amin.

02:01:41.510 --> 02:01:45.510
Names given, His Excellency Idi
Amin, the Butcher of Uganda,

02:01:45.510 --> 02:01:49.690
Conqueror of the British Empire in
Africa and Uganda in particular,

02:01:49.690 --> 02:01:54.880
Field Marshal Alhaji, Doctor,
Big Daddy, President for Life,

02:01:54.880 --> 02:01:58.690
Lord of all the beasts of the
Earth and fishes of the sea.

02:01:58.690 --> 02:02:00.320
Weight, 250.

02:02:00.320 --> 02:02:02.190
Height, 6-4.

02:02:02.190 --> 02:02:05.550
What his former British
commander said, "A splendid type,

02:02:05.550 --> 02:02:11.390
a good rugby player, and a reliable
soldier, cheerful, energetic,

02:02:11.390 --> 02:02:17.610
and an incredible person
who certainly isn't mad."

02:02:17.610 --> 02:02:22.780
First instance of torture, 1962
Turkana Massacre, burying alive,

02:02:22.780 --> 02:02:26.170
beating to death, et
cetera, overlooked.

02:02:26.170 --> 02:02:30.240
Promoted to head of
armed forces, 1963.

02:02:30.240 --> 02:02:33.870
Awards, distinguished service
order, Victoria's Cross,

02:02:33.870 --> 02:02:36.640
Military Cross, Doctor of Law.

02:02:36.640 --> 02:02:41.650
Seizes power backed by Israel
and Great Britain, 1971.

02:02:41.650 --> 02:02:44.120
Number of wives, four.

02:02:44.120 --> 02:02:46.140
Mistresses, 30.

02:02:46.140 --> 02:02:48.540
Abused, 34.

02:02:48.540 --> 02:02:53.010
Number of soldiers employed in
special death squads, 18,000.

02:02:53.010 --> 02:02:56.280
Number of villagers
wiped out, unknown.

02:02:56.280 --> 02:03:02.060
Kill count, 300,000,
or 1 in 26 people.

02:03:02.060 --> 02:03:06.370
Flees to Libya in 1979
after losing war

02:03:06.370 --> 02:03:09.990
with Tanzanian forces
and Ugandan dissidents.

02:03:09.990 --> 02:03:15.790
Motto, in any country, there
must be people who have to die.

02:03:15.790 --> 02:03:22.650
This one is called "Exodus,
Fathers, Americans Superheroes."

02:03:22.650 --> 02:03:27.290
Because certain death, because
genocide, he leads them out.

02:03:27.290 --> 02:03:31.920
He is Moses and Jeremiah
when no one else will try.

02:03:31.920 --> 02:03:34.110
The faith to move mountains and get

02:03:34.110 --> 02:03:38.790
to America keep them
secret, keep them safe.

02:03:38.790 --> 02:03:40.800
Raise up his body family.

02:03:40.800 --> 02:03:42.100
Begin again.

02:03:42.100 --> 02:03:45.550
This one's called "Mouth."

02:03:45.550 --> 02:03:48.280
They pack nothing to
escape detection.

02:03:48.280 --> 02:03:50.450
One change of clothes.

02:03:50.450 --> 02:03:53.750 position:56%
No books, furniture, or photographs.

02:03:53.750 --> 02:03:57.770
My father's lab specimens
are sewn into his pants.

02:03:57.770 --> 02:04:00.710
A day trip with our daughter,
they will say at the border.

02:04:00.710 --> 02:04:05.870
We will be right back.

02:04:05.870 --> 02:04:08.290
This one is "Breath."

02:04:08.290 --> 02:04:12.740
They never speak of the dead,
the massacres, at school.

02:04:12.740 --> 02:04:15.400
Friends and family disappeared.

02:04:15.400 --> 02:04:18.520
How they got word they were next.

02:04:18.520 --> 02:04:22.290 position:56%
The crossing to Kenya, then America.

02:04:22.290 --> 02:04:26.820
What happened to those left behind?

02:04:26.820 --> 02:04:31.970
This poem is called "Numbers."

02:04:31.970 --> 02:04:34.560
Mother makes the doll
after their baby boy

02:04:34.560 --> 02:04:37.680
who would have been
my older brother dies.

02:04:37.680 --> 02:04:42.000
She sews his bits of curly black
hair on top, pricks his finger

02:04:42.000 --> 02:04:46.940
with her needles, paints his
blood on the cotton-stuffed face.

02:04:46.940 --> 02:04:53.420 position:56%
Two circles for eyes, two lines for
nose and mouth, and she is finished.

02:04:53.420 --> 02:04:57.890
All the time father is away,
she will hold baby boy doll

02:04:57.890 --> 02:05:01.310
and hum the many melodies
she learned to sing

02:05:01.310 --> 02:05:05.000
when a hospital nurse
back home in Amin's war

02:05:05.000 --> 02:05:09.090
to the skin-thin shivering
rib caged infants,

02:05:09.090 --> 02:05:14.660
tiny orphaned fists flailing
to eat their last bit of feces

02:05:14.660 --> 02:05:17.800
that would not keep
them alive another day.

02:05:17.800 --> 02:05:22.330 position:56%
The lightness of their bodies in
her arms, no heavier than the breath

02:05:22.330 --> 02:05:24.720
of air that was her song.

02:05:24.720 --> 02:05:30.270 position:56%
And that one came from a dream I had
when I was pregnant with my own son

02:05:30.270 --> 02:05:33.060
and I began to have all these
memories I couldn't know

02:05:33.060 --> 02:05:34.360
and that was one of them.

02:05:34.360 --> 02:05:36.360
And I called my mom and I
said, "Did you tell this to me

02:05:36.360 --> 02:05:39.510
about being a nurse and
the babies, orphans,

02:05:39.510 --> 02:05:42.510
newborns not having enough milk
because their parents were dead

02:05:42.510 --> 02:05:44.260
and them dying of hunger?"

02:05:44.260 --> 02:05:45.560
And she said, "No.

02:05:45.560 --> 02:05:46.860
I didn't tell that you."

02:05:46.860 --> 02:05:48.160
But somehow, that memory came up

02:05:48.160 --> 02:05:50.850
and that fascinates me,
that cultural memory.

02:05:50.850 --> 02:05:53.150
So this one's called "The Nerve."

02:05:53.150 --> 02:05:57.290
I've never read this one before
aloud, but, again, it seemed timely

02:05:57.290 --> 02:05:59.790
to be here in this
town, in this place,

02:05:59.790 --> 02:06:01.950
at this time and read this poem.

02:06:01.950 --> 02:06:03.300
So it's a little long.

02:06:03.300 --> 02:06:07.530
So bear with me and I'll just
read two more after this.

02:06:07.530 --> 02:06:09.490
"The Nerve."

02:06:09.490 --> 02:06:11.180
When I was a little girl, you

02:06:11.180 --> 02:06:13.900
and I were the best of
friends, dear father.

02:06:13.900 --> 02:06:17.290
As I followed you down the
long test tube flanked aisles

02:06:17.290 --> 02:06:20.560
of your laboratory
funded by the same people

02:06:20.560 --> 02:06:24.800
who had enslaved your grandparents
and bankrupted your country

02:06:24.800 --> 02:06:27.970
and would deny them the
medicines you were discovering,

02:06:27.970 --> 02:06:32.880 position:56%
still following you in stores, still
sending cops to watch our house,

02:06:32.880 --> 02:06:35.470
because those niggers have been
up to no good since we moved

02:06:35.470 --> 02:06:40.400
to our town, I wanted to know why
and wrote down everything you said

02:06:40.400 --> 02:06:45.830
as truth until I began to think for
myself and you couldn't have that.

02:06:45.830 --> 02:06:49.570
So you began to beat at me
like a housewife does a stain,

02:06:49.570 --> 02:06:53.250
as if that would get
the education out.

02:06:53.250 --> 02:06:56.580
The doctors have said you will
spend this year dying and I want

02:06:56.580 --> 02:06:58.560
to tell you so many things.

02:06:58.560 --> 02:07:00.840
But yesterday, they
let free that white man

02:07:00.840 --> 02:07:04.630
who killed a little brown
boy just because he was brown

02:07:04.630 --> 02:07:07.410
and the day before that, they
took away our right to vote

02:07:07.410 --> 02:07:08.870
and the day before that,

02:07:08.870 --> 02:07:11.160
they released a study
saying the radiation

02:07:11.160 --> 02:07:15.240
from a nuclear disaster exploded
in Japan has already jumped

02:07:15.240 --> 02:07:19.820 position:56%
in the water, swum across the ocean,
up through our faucets, our hoses,

02:07:19.820 --> 02:07:22.480 position:56%
into our earth, plants, and animals,

02:07:22.480 --> 02:07:25.520
our bodies now dying,
infected already.

02:07:25.520 --> 02:07:29.380
And there is not enough medicine
for everyone and you know

02:07:29.380 --> 02:07:32.730
who there will not be enough for.

02:07:32.730 --> 02:07:37.460
This morning I had to stop while
doing my yoga and curl into a ball,

02:07:37.460 --> 02:07:40.030
hold myself to keep from shaking.

02:07:40.030 --> 02:07:43.050
All day long, I felt terrified.

02:07:43.050 --> 02:07:46.960
Little spasms down my spine
and central nervous system.

02:07:46.960 --> 02:07:49.910
As I remember taking
my seven-month-old son

02:07:49.910 --> 02:07:55.700
for our daily walk because he loves
outside, outside, and I love him,

02:07:55.700 --> 02:07:58.150
walking with him pressed
against my body,

02:07:58.150 --> 02:08:03.400
still feeling my bones realigning,
muscles unwinding from giving birth

02:08:03.400 --> 02:08:07.790
to him, carrying him, and the old
white man who lives in the house

02:08:07.790 --> 02:08:10.320
on the corner yelling
he would shoot us

02:08:10.320 --> 02:08:14.830
like that other white man had
the other little brown boy just

02:08:14.830 --> 02:08:16.800
because we are brown too.

02:08:16.800 --> 02:08:19.490
And all I could think was breathe.

02:08:19.490 --> 02:08:24.050
Breathe. There are
people's small horrors too.

02:08:24.050 --> 02:08:28.140
A friend who was trying to get
pregnant, another miscarriage,

02:08:28.140 --> 02:08:30.180
says it feels like meeting a ghost

02:08:30.180 --> 02:08:33.520
without ever having
met the person before.

02:08:33.520 --> 02:08:37.110
And I just want you, my
father, to protect me,

02:08:37.110 --> 02:08:41.360
teach me how to protect my son,
because they have put in a law

02:08:41.360 --> 02:08:46.130
that says the last man standing can
say, "I felt threatened," and shoot

02:08:46.130 --> 02:08:48.690
to kill and then walk free.

02:08:48.690 --> 02:08:52.600
And they always say they
are threatened by us

02:08:52.600 --> 02:08:55.820
and they have taken away the other
law that says they cannot stop

02:08:55.820 --> 02:08:57.390
in front of our path --

02:08:57.390 --> 02:09:01.370
step in front of our path to
the voting house and stop us.

02:09:01.370 --> 02:09:05.140
And they have never
stopped trying to stop us.

02:09:05.140 --> 02:09:08.360
And I wonder what is to
stop them from firing,

02:09:08.360 --> 02:09:12.760 position:56%
knowing their whiteness is their
ticket to not guilty, to be set free

02:09:12.760 --> 02:09:17.720
of having to feel their rage of
having a man who looks like you

02:09:17.720 --> 02:09:20.350
in their White House again.

02:09:28.410 --> 02:09:32.060
This one is called "Refugee Minds."

02:09:32.060 --> 02:09:36.270
And my son had [inaudible]
one of his little friends

02:09:36.270 --> 02:09:39.640
and we was talking to her
mom and she was telling me

02:09:39.640 --> 02:09:42.590
about the banyan tree that grows
in Hawaii and I never heard of it

02:09:42.590 --> 02:09:46.320
and it's the tree that grows up
and then its roots and limbs,

02:09:46.320 --> 02:09:48.920
instead of going outward,
grow back down into the ground

02:09:48.920 --> 02:09:50.360
and then it grows up again.

02:09:50.360 --> 02:09:54.320
And that image stuck with me
and said exactly what I needed.

02:09:54.320 --> 02:09:57.560
So I have to thank my son for
choosing really wonderful friends

02:09:57.560 --> 02:10:01.680
who have really wonderful
moms who give me poems.

02:10:01.680 --> 02:10:04.070
So "Refugee Minds."

02:10:04.070 --> 02:10:08.320
They thought believing would
be like the banyan tree rising

02:10:08.320 --> 02:10:14.700 position:56%
to spread wide, branches turned down
become root again, grow new life.

02:10:14.700 --> 02:10:18.300
But there is work that must
be done to connect deep

02:10:18.300 --> 02:10:21.390
and strong inside alien ground.

02:10:21.390 --> 02:10:23.180
You must speak.

02:10:23.180 --> 02:10:26.960
You must let yourself be
known by these new children

02:10:26.960 --> 02:10:31.190
and all your glorious
tangled mess of becoming.

02:10:31.190 --> 02:10:33.140
Your culture also.

02:10:33.140 --> 02:10:34.440
Burrow down deep in this.

02:10:34.440 --> 02:10:39.980
Else for there are
always storms coming.

02:10:39.980 --> 02:10:42.950
Rootless, apart, you break.

02:10:42.950 --> 02:10:49.050
And my last two poems, very
quickly, this one is "Naomi."

02:10:50.710 --> 02:10:53.760
When grandmother listens,
my mouth is alien,

02:10:53.760 --> 02:10:57.260
foreign waters lapping
at a foreign shore.

02:10:57.260 --> 02:11:00.850
I have only the language
of her conquerors

02:11:00.850 --> 02:11:04.210
within just one small island.

02:11:04.210 --> 02:11:11.470
Kuhu [assumed spelling], Kuhu,
her name repeated become a song.

02:11:11.470 --> 02:11:16.350
And my last poem I wanted to read
for you, "Slow Dance with Bullet."

02:11:16.350 --> 02:11:19.260
Again, felt like I'm here
in this town so I needed

02:11:19.260 --> 02:11:22.060
to read this poem to you.

02:11:22.060 --> 02:11:24.250
"Slow Dance with Bullet."

02:11:24.250 --> 02:11:27.090
This is when you become political.

02:11:27.090 --> 02:11:31.650
This unarmed black boy shot,
this white killer cop not charge,

02:11:31.650 --> 02:11:35.790
but given three months paid
vacation, plus $1 million

02:11:35.790 --> 02:11:38.690
in thanks for this job well done.

02:11:38.690 --> 02:11:42.250
This happened yesterday,
too, the day before that.

02:11:42.250 --> 02:11:45.590
They used to say this,
"Dance, nigger, dance,

02:11:45.590 --> 02:11:48.190
and empty their guns laughing."

02:11:48.190 --> 02:11:50.040
This was their theory.

02:11:50.040 --> 02:11:54.560
If you can rise fast enough, the
bullets would not hit your feet.

02:11:54.560 --> 02:11:59.720
This, the weight of five centuries
that did not break your back.

02:11:59.720 --> 02:12:01.780
This, you are scared of, then.

02:12:01.780 --> 02:12:05.390
This, you stiffen silent and bored.

02:12:05.390 --> 02:12:08.890
This will happen again
tomorrow, different city,

02:12:08.890 --> 02:12:13.680
different dead black boy body,
but now, the straw needle.

02:12:13.680 --> 02:12:17.750
Oh, how your baby boy
loves to dance.

02:12:17.750 --> 02:12:20.060
His legs, though, are little.

02:12:20.060 --> 02:12:21.680
He could never jump enough.

02:12:21.680 --> 02:12:24.510
Thank you so much.

